The Pathfinders emerge into ancient ruins located in the Winterlands on the planet of Akiton. Here, they encounter creatures stranded by the Maze of the Open Road, ancient traps and guardians, and dead displaced through time. This entry chamber has four major features of note: the Eternity Arch, an ablution chamber, a dressing chamber, and an ovoid vault.

The PCs can choose to examine the features in the immediate area before proceeding to the next room. If the PCs spend more than 10 minutes in this area, move them along to the main encounters in this part.

Ablution Chamber: This side chamber contains a fountain that pours water into a large stone washing basin. The water is clean, clear, and tastes metallic. A PC who succeeds at a @Check[religion|dc:15|traits:action:recall-knowledge,secret] check realizes this is an ablution chamber, used to ritually wash before entering a sacred space.

Dressing Chamber: Three rows of wooden hooks protrude from the stone walls in a line around the perimeter of this side chamber, one row at 3 feet above the ground, one at 5, and one at 9. A black wood bench is in the chamber's center. A PC who succeeds at a @Check[society|dc:20|traits:action:recall-knowledge,secret] check realizes this is a dressing chamber, which would have held clothes for creatures varying from Small to Large in size.

Eternity Arch: The arch in the chamber's center is 15 feet wide, 25 feet tall, and constructed of a luminous crystal that sheds bright light. A PC who succeeds at a @Check[arcana,religion|dc:20|traits:action:identify-magic,secret] check to Identify Magic determines the arch is a powerful artifact with a connection to another plane. On a critical success, they realize the arch is releasing a barely audible hum as it resonates with something elsewhere in the ruins. Ashasar is impressed by any information the PCs offer him and assures them he'll investigate further while they tend to their duties.

Ovoid Vault: The entrance to this ovoid chamber is only partially blocked by a circular stone door, which slides in and out of the wall. The red stone chamber is completely curved, with no angles or hard edges anywhere. The chamber is empty, but half of the PCs that enter this chamber see a large grey and blue container in the center, similar to a sarcophagus, constructed from metal and glass. A PC who attempts to touch the box feels nothing—their hand passes right through, causing the box to flicker in and out of sight rapidly. That PC hears a jumble of words—"for," "me," "no," "run," and "wait" among them—and then the box vanishes completely for that PC. A character who witnesses the box flicker out of sight and succeeds at an @Check[arcana,occultism|dc:20|traits:action:identify-magic,secret] check to Identify Magic believes the box was a temporal malfunction—the box exists in another time and shouldn't have been visible at all. If any PCs attempt to close the door, Eando Kline approaches and shakes his head, telling the Pathfinders not to meddle unnecessarily.

Exit: The chamber's massive exit door is made of pitchblack stone. On the other side of the door (the side that faces the next room), there are six faintly glowing glyphs. Outside the chamber's exit, numerous branching halls and passages lead to the encounter areas. The PCs can do the following five encounters in any order. These encounters all take place on the same day, and the PCs can take time to Treat Wounds, Refocus, or Repair equipment in between encounters. These encounters don't need to be run in any particular order. The players have 90 minutes to complete as many missions as they can.

Note: The following is a handout that is similar to what has been provided in recent specials to help the players choose: @UUID[JournalEntry.kZ3zpd8KVWsQZ4xc.JournalEntryPage.jKzDgRqwE3840XR9]{Mission Descriptions: Part 1}

There are five conditions the House GM might announce, each tied to the House completing an objective in one of the five mission locations. Some of these benefits apply to the whole table at once, while others allow each player to activate them individually.

As the PCs are coming from the Eternity Arch, they are technically progressing through these ruins backwards. When a PC steps on the central bridge, the constructs begin to advance and then proceed to attack.

B1: The Trapped Hall

When the Maze of the Open Road first began malfunctioning, Dalver (NG male half-elf botanist) was inside and engaged in battle against a group of territorial wolverines. He and his companion, Carine (CN female human sneak), fled out the maze's nearest exit, only to wind up in these ancient ruins. Much to their surprise, some of the wolverines followed. Within this trapped hall, Dalver was wounded, Carine fled to area B3, one wolverine was killed, and the others retreated. Dalver has lost a lot of blood and is barely conscious.

Hazards: There are four poison dart traps down this long hall, as marked on the map.

A character who understands Draconic knows the creatures on the other side are discussing how they're going to get back home to the maze with the "monster dogs" around. These are kobolds from the Thornscale clan, and they live within the Maze of the Open Road, which they were pulled into accidentally a few years ago. Recognizing the maze as a place of power, they chose to remain within it even after the Pathfinders and Eliza Petulengro repaired it during the events of Pathfinder Society Scenario #1-21: Mistress of the Maze. These kobolds left the maze to hunt and wound up here, where they were chased by a "monster dog" (actually a hound of Tindalos in pursuit of Heraxia). Afraid and confused, they barricaded themselves in this chamber. They suspect anyone nearby is the master of the "monster dogs" sent to hunt them. When the kobolds notice the party, they fall silent and hide behind their barricades.

Hazards: The kobolds have set a trap outside their shelter, which triggers when anyone enters the marked areas.

Creatures: After the PCs trigger the or disable it, the kobolds yell in Draconic, "Back off! You won't keep us here forever! The Thornscales will escape you and your monster dog!" If the party doesn't understand draconic, the kobolds switch to Common if they hear any of the PCs speak in that language. Itzi (CG female kobold thorn-blessed), a green kobold with a laurel of red roses atop her head, leads the group. A PC who succeeds at a @Check[nature|dc:16|traits:secret] check recognizes that these flowers are Narven's Tears, an otherwise extinct breed of rose that still grows within the Maze of the Open Road. The PCs can try to convince the kobolds they're here to help. The kobolds give the PCs sufficient time to speak before attacking, although they remain behind their barricade. If a PC attacks or attempts to bypass the barricade, the kobolds attack. Each PC can attempt a @Check[deception,diplomacy|dc:15|traits:kobold-friend] check to influence the kobolds. A character who is a kobold, speaks Draconic, or mentions the Maze of the Open Road gains a +1 circumstance bonus on these checks.

@UUID[Item.djMH1D99d8VrLrP4]{Effect: Friend of Kobolds}

Critical Success The PCs earn 2 Friendship Points.

Success The PCs earn 1 Friendship Point.

Critical Failure The PCs lose 1 Friendship Point.

If the PCs earn at least as many Friendship Points as half the number of PCs, they convince the kobolds that they mean no harm. Otherwise, the kobolds leap out and attack.

Development: If the PCs befriend the Thornscale kobolds, the kobolds share their tale and allow the party into their base. They describe the "monster dog" as hairless, gray, and sickly, with bulging eyes and a long tongue.

Temporal Pools: Behind the kobold barricade are three large pools, each 10 feet in diameter and filled with a different colored fluid. This ancient device is a temporal scrying mechanism that siphons energy from the Dimension of Time and harnesses it to view the past, present, and future. The degradation of time has diminished their powers; they function erratically and what times they view can't be controlled or manipulated. A PC can discern the device's function with a successful @Check[arcana,crafting,engineering-lore,occultism|dc:16|adjustment:1,0,0,1|traits:action:identify-magic,secret]

Paxle and Uby (N male and female nykteras) are a pair of bat sprites who live within the Maze of the Open Road. A Hylki scholar with deep-crimson skin and orange eyes takes notes at his desk. Uby is bound to a pedestal at the lab's center by three straps. Unlatching and removing one of the intricate straps requires two Interact actions.

The Akitonian ruin has the following features.

Gravity: Akiton has low gravity. The Bulk of all creatures and objects is halved, meaning creatures acclimated to normal gravity (such as the PCs) can carry twice as much and jump twice as high and far. Physical ranged attacks are possible up to the twelfth range increment (instead of the sixth). A creature that falls in low gravity takes no damage for the first 10 feet of the fall, and then takes bludgeoning damage equal to a quarter of the remaining distance fallen.

Language across Time: The voices of creatures from the future are heavily entangled in temporal distortions, and they have picked up fragments of the evolution of all of the languages that have ever been spoken in this ruin. The same entanglement applies to written language from the future, such as the words on the Starfinder Society supply crate in area H. Whenever the PCs encounter language from the future, they find it perfectly comprehensible, but they notice occasional stutters, ripples, and other signs of temporal distortion.

Light: The entire ruin is in darkness unless otherwise noted.

Time Rifts: As the PCs travel through the ruins, they often notice little rifts in time. In addition to the effects listed in the scenario, GMs are welcome to describe the PCs witnessing visions of events that took place earlier in the scenario, such as the most entertaining or consequential parts of previous encounters.

When all paths of the Pathfinder's Maze of the Open Road—a recently repaired extradimensional shortcut that enables rapid travel throughout Golarion—turn toward a single unknown location, the Pathfinders launch an expedition to the Maze's new destination. There, in long-abandoned ruins, they discover a powerful artifact known as the Eternity Arch, which is acting as a planar beacon as it resonates with something deeper in the ruins. To free the Maze of the Open Road from the grasp of the Eternity Arch, the Pathfinders search for the source of the resonance. At the ruin's surface entrance, the Pathfinders discover their target—a dragonkin from the future separated from her partner during a temporal escapade and stranded in the present. The Pathfinders must protect the dragonkin long enough to help send her home, then quickly flee through the Maze of the Open Road or be stranded forever on an alien world!

In the distant future, across an immeasurable gulf of time, a dragonkin named Heraxia and her bonded ryphorian partner, Felise, dabbled in mischief and misadventure. They embarked on countless ill-conceived schemes, each more daring than the last. Soon, the duo's foolhardy adventures were taking place not on distant worlds but distant planes. Felise's newfound passion for exploring forbidden temporal byways, however, attracted the attention of hounds of Tindalos during one of their journeys. Outnumbered and overpowered, the two fled, and during the chase, they stumbled upon a fissure in the Dimension of Time. They sought to use it to escape, but the unstable fissure instead caused a terrible temporal accident, and the two were separated. While Felise returned home to their original timeline, Heraxia was shunted backward in time—to the present.

Even across such a distance, Heraxia and Felise have still been able to empathically communicate for brief periods. In the years since their separation, they've employed numerous artifacts, magical rituals, and experimental technology to try to bring Heraxia back to the future, and none have worked. Fortuitously, they've both recently come across a magical artifact known as the Eternity Arch in their respective timelines and believe it could finally provide an answer to their long isolation. Though the arch was originally intended for psychic transference across time, Heraxia and Felise have been independently experimenting on it to modify it, in the hopes of finally bringing Heraxia back home.

Their tinkering has had consequences in both timelines. In the distant future, Felise's meddling has led to rumors of haunted ruins hidden in Akiton's southern glaciers, drawing the Starfinder Society's attention. In the present, Heraxia's attempts to attune to the Eternity Arch has caused the pair to function as a powerful beacon that cuts across time and space, attracting dimensional pathways—pathways like the Maze of the Open Road.

The Maze of the Open Road is a magical hedge maze that enables its wanderers to walk interdimensional pathways to reach distant destinations in a short time. Since its creation, the Maze has included portals to many locations across Golarion and beyond. Thanks to the efforts of numerous Pathfinder agents, the Pathfinder Society was able to establish some degree of control over its destinations and add several Pathfinder lodges to the network, including the newly founded Open Road Lodge. Now, the Maze's exits have realigned and all lead to a single unknown destination: the lair of the Eternity Arch. Initial investigations by the Pathfinder Society indicate the trouble lies not within the Maze of the Open Road but beyond it.

By order of the Pathfinder Society's Decemvirate leadership, Venture-Captain Armeline Jirneau of the Woodsedge Lodge has assembled a large expedition to travel into the Maze of the Open Road, to determine the source of the anomaly and resolve it. The Pathfinder and Starfinder Societies launch parallel explorations into the Akitonian ruin containing the Eternity Arch, their investigations on a collision course across time itself.

The introduction of Fate in the Future takes place at Woodsedge Lodge in Galt. During Part 1, the PCs quickly traverse the Maze of the Open Road to a mysterious ruin. This ruin is in the Winterlands of Akiton, the fourth planet from the sun in Golarion's solar system. You can find information on Woodsedge Lodge beginning on page 106 of the Lost Omens Pathfinder Society Guide, on Galt beginning on page 126 of the Pathfinder Lost Omens World Guide, and on Akiton on page 16 of Pathfinder Campaign Setting: Distant Worlds. For information on Akiton during the Starfinder era, see page 442 of the Starfinder Core Rulebook and page 48 of Starfinder Pact Worlds.

Fate in the Future is meant to accommodate varying House sizes (from 6 tables up to 150+ tables). To facilitate a more cohesive process for seating players at larger events, the introduction and player mustering phases are built into the scenario during the introduction. There is no requirement to have everyone seated before players begin the introduction, and Table GMs should be ready to start as soon as four or more players have been seated at the table.

Because of the nature of mustering, players may need to be moved from one table to another to achieve minimum numbers or table balance. If players whose tables are already underway are asked to move, the Table GM should encourage them to bring along any information they discovered at their initial table and share it with their new table.

This scenario has two versions: one designed for levels 1–4 and one for levels 5–8. When assigning and adjusting tables, remember that PCs can play at a table only if their level falls within the range for that version. Each of these versions counts as a separate scenario. Players and GMs may earn credit for each of these two versions once.

For ease of running this event, text intended for Table GMs to read aloud is orange, while text intended for the House GM to read aloud is blue.

Fate in the Future uses several terms unique to Organized Play interactive events. Each participant's role in the event is outlined under the respective entry.

Challenge Points: This is a measure of the PCs' overall strength that Pathfinder Society s cenarios use to adjust difficulty of encounters for groups of varying sizes and levels.

House GM: This Game Master manages the timing, scoring, and flow of the event. In addition, they make announcements about the amount of time remaining and events that impact the entire House, as well as presenting the opening and closing scenes of the adventure. The House GM should have some means of signaling to the entire House, especially Table GMs, who are their liaisons to the players. This can be through a bell or other auditory signal that can cut through the din of a room full of excited players, or it could be a visual signal like a flashing light or waving flag. The signal indicates that everyone in the House should be silent and direct their attention to the House GM.

The House GM should inform all Table GMs what this signal is prior to the event's start and ensure that they are all positioned to be able to see or hear it during the event.

House: All the PCs participating in the adventure across all levels.

HQ Staff: These are support personnel who tabulate results and handle player table assignments at the beginning of the event. Members of the HQ Staff are responsible for managing the results of table actions during the event.

Mustering: The process of gathering up players and assigning groups of players to GMs.

Part: This event is broken into four separate segments. To a degree, each individual table can move through encounters at its own pace, but the entire House starts and ends each part simultaneously to ensure the stage of play remains synchronized across the entire House.

Table GM: Each of these Game Masters manages a single table of players. Tables are run exactly like one would run a standard Pathfinder Society table, with the following exceptions. Table GMs must follow the instructions for getting the PCs to the next part in the scenario. Likewise, if a Table GM has a group that finishes the part before the House GM calls time, they must notify the House GM.

Fate in the Future is designed to take less than 5 hours, including a modest amount of time for mustering and setup. Each section transitions automatically after a certain amount of time passes, though the introduction is somewhat flexible based on mustering needs. The following is a measure of how long each part should last.

Introduction: 15 minutes (or longer, if mustering requires)

Part 1: 90 minutes

Part 2: 80 minutes

Part 3: 30 minutes

Part 4: 60 minutes

Conclusion: 15 minutes

This adventure includes references to ancestries and cultures that the PCs are unlikely to be familiar with. When the PC s interact with someone from one of these ancestries, whether by talking to them or seeing a vision that includes them, the PCs can attempt a @Check[society|dc:25] check to learn the relevant information below.

Dragonkin: Dragonkin are an ancestry of bipedal dragons native to Triaxus. They form close, lifetime bonds with a single other person, and they often choose ryphorians as their partners.

Human: Most humans on Akiton belong to a broad category of ethnicities called Hylki. Hylki people have deep-crimson skin and eyes that tend toward warm colors like yellow, orange, and red.

Ikeshti: Ikeshtis are a small, draconic-featured people with reddish scales who live primarily in Akiton's deserts and hills.

Kasatha: Kasathas are humanoids with four arms and long craniums. A small number of kasathas live on Golarion, in the deserts of Numeria. While these kasathas know that their ancestors come from another planet far beyond Golarion's solar system, their history is shrouded in contradictory legends.

Ratfolk: Ratfolk are far more prevalent on Akiton than they are on Golarion. Some scholars believe that the term ysoki, which many ratfolk on Golarion use to describe themselves, may have originated from Akitonian ratfolk, who use the same term.

Ryphorian: Ryphorians are so prevalent on Triaxus that those from other planets sometimes refer to them simply as Triaxians. Ryphorians' physical characteristics depend upon the season of their birth, with summerborn ryphorians having dark skin and winterborn ryphorians having white fur. These features come in handy, as Triaxus's seasons last for several centuries.

Shobhad: Shobhads are 12-foot-tall humanoids with four arms and gray skin. Most shobhads on Akiton live in clans whose cultures prizes resilience, self-sufficiency, and martial prowess.

Heraxia should be familiar to the PCs, as they've had the opportunity to see and hear her multiple times through time rifts and other visions during the course of this event. After brief introductions, Heraxia shares what she remembers about herself and her dilemma.

  • Heraxia comes from what she thinks is distant future. She was born on Triaxus (another planet) and bonded with an adventurous ryphorian named Felise.
  • The duo went on many adventures, thought Heraxia can't recall specifics. She does recall Felise was easily bored and insisted each adventure was bigger, bolder, and more dangerous than the last. They explored other worlds, planes, and eventually other times.
  • Their travels through temporal byways attracted the attention of dangerous beasts, particularly strange bug-eyed hounds that hunted them. The pair fled but were separated. Felise was shunted back to their home time, while Heraxia was stranded in the distant past.
  • Heraxia and Felise retained the ability to communicate empathically, but it happens rarely and for short periods.
  • In the years since their separation, they've employed numerous artifacts, magical rituals, and experimental technology to try to bring Heraxia back to the future, all in vain.
  • Fortuitously, they've both recently come across a magical artifact known as the Eternity Arch in their respective timelines and believe it could at last provide an answer to their long isolation. Though the arch was originally intended for psychic transference across time, Heraxia has found a damaged stasis pod transplanted here from another time. Once repaired, it should serve as the perfect vessel for Heraxia to travel through the Eternity Arch to her home time. Both Felise and Heraxia have been independently experimenting and modifying the Eternity Arch to accommodate Heraxia's journey. This is why the arch is resonating with Heraxia (and why the Maze of the Open Road is malfunctioning)

pages.name: The Maze of the Open Road

text.content:
Venture-Captain Armeline Jirneau calls for all Pathfinders to gather for an announcement. Once everyone is finished mustering, the House GM reads or paraphrases the following.

A hush falls over the gathered Pathfinders as Venture-Captain Armeline Jirneau ascends a podium erected outside the entrance to the Maze of the Open Road. "Welcome to Woodsedge, Pathfinders! Thank you for coming. As many of you know, the Maze of the Open Road is an interdimensional pathway built long ago by Forest King Narven Feathereyes as a gift for the Society. Time was not kind to the maze, but thanks to the efforts of Eliza Petulengro and other Pathfinders, it was repaired."

"Recently, the maze's paths realigned and now all point to a single location. Our investigations indicate this isn't a problem with the Maze of the Open Road but an outside source—a beacon—that's attracting the paths. The maze is of critical importance to many missions and must remain available. Our mission is to fix this strange anomaly."

"We traverse the Maze of the Open Road to an unknown destination. Although this is an exciting opportunity to explore new horizons, our mission is not exploration. Our mission is to find the beacon and sever its connection to the Maze of the Open Road. Prepare yourselves! We leave shortly."

This text alerts Table GMs that they need to wrap up the preparations section and prepare to begin Part 1. Once every table is ready (provide about 5 minutes), the House GM reads or paraphrases the following text.

"Stay close," Venture-Captain Armeline Jirneau calls out as she leads the assembled Pathfinders into the Maze of the Open Road. "We won't be here long."

Armeline guides the Pathfinders through the maze with confidence, while Eando Kline, faction leader of the Vigilant Seal, takes the rear, ensuring no Pathfinders get left behind. Armeline hesitates only a moment before plunging through a shimmering portal, out of the Maze and into the unknown.

The Pathfinders arrive in a large stone chamber with red stone walls and polished tan floor tiles, lit by a luminous arch rising from a central raised platform. The chamber has three side chambers and one exit.

"Fan out, Pathfinders!" Venture-Captain Armeline orders. "Secure the area."
